The SevenDecor Prism is provided by `sevenos-window-controls.service`. It stays
collapsed and translucent by default; clicking it exposes red, yellow and green.
Red closes the active window, yellow toggles floating/tiling, green applies
smart maximize and green double-click enters fullscreen. Drag the Prism to move
it; double-click it to return to automatic active-window follow mode. Right-click
or long press opens the advanced menu: split left/right, scratchpad, pin/unpin,
move to workspace, target lock/unlock, focus mode, hide for the active app and
reset placement. When expanded, a compact chip shows the target window; when it
is locked, actions keep applying to that window even after focus changes. Click
that chip to lock or unlock directly; scroll on it to cycle through workspace
windows and lock the chosen target. Prism labels and tooltips follow the
language configured in SevenOS or in the system.

```bash
seven-window controls-start
seven-window controls-stop
seven-window controls-toggle
seven-window controls-effect toggle
seven-window controls-effect off
seven-window controls-items
seven-window controls-item add settings
seven-window controls-item add terminal
seven-window controls-item custom browser Browser B firefox
seven-window controls-item set daily
seven-window controls-item set dev
seven-window controls-item move terminal up
seven-window controls-item remove settings
seven-window controls-item clear
seven-window controls-status
seven-window layout-menu
seven-window advanced-menu
seven-window controls-unlock
seven-window controls-reset-hidden
seven-window decor-status --json
```

