## SevenOS Bar And Control Center

- Profile opens the Profile Center.
- Spotlight opens global search.
- Wi-Fi opens the friendly Wi-Fi panel.
- Bluetooth opens the Bluetooth panel.
- Sound opens audio controls.
- Battery opens power controls.
- Control Center opens quick settings.
- Notifications are integrated in Control Center, and the panel closes when it
  loses focus so it does not block Settings or password prompts.

Useful commands:

```bash
seven new
seven status
seven doctor
seven post-install
seven repair ux --apply
seven profile requirements all --json
seven profile requirements forge --apply --yes
seven profile-rootfs audit all
seven profile-rootfs verify all
seven actions
seven spotlight index
seven-quick-settings
seven-quick-settings wifi
seven-quick-settings bluetooth
seven-quick-settings audio
seven-quick-settings power
seven-wifi status-json
seven-bluetooth status-json
```

Mini OS requirements follow the real boundary: Equinox is checked against the
host, while Forge, Shield, Studio, Baobab, Atlas and Pulse are checked against
their private rootfs. A package present in Forge does not need to be globally
installed in Equinox for Forge to be complete.

## SevenOS Actions

Actions are the common language of the system. The same action can be exposed in
Spotlight, Waybar, Seven Hub, SevenAI, notifications and app menus.

| Source | Role |
| --- | --- |
| `seven actions` | lists available user actions |
| `seven actions --json` | machine-readable format for native surfaces |
| `seven-waybar-action` | executes actions from the SevenOS bar |
| `seven-waybar-context` | reports active app, service, profile and media context |
| `seven-spotlight` | searches and launches actions, apps and files |
| `seven ai` | previews and applies actions with confirmation |

Useful commands:

```bash
seven actions
seven actions --json
seven-waybar-context --json
seven-waybar-action app-menu
seven spotlight index
seven ai "open files"
```

## Themes And Appearance

Light/dark mode is global to SevenOS. Mini OS profiles mainly change accents,
priorities and surfaces, not the complete mode.

| Need | Command |
| --- | --- |
| Apply light theme | `./install.sh theme light` |
| Apply dark theme | `./install.sh theme dark` |
| Check theme state | `seven theme doctor` |
| Repair visual UX | `seven repair ux --apply` |
| Reload Hyprland/Waybar | `seven hypr apply` |
| Terminal transparent/solid | `Ctrl+Shift+B` inside Seven Terminal |

Seven Terminal uses the wallpaper-derived theme when available:

- text is automatically corrected for contrast;
- transparent background by default with the `◐` button;
- `SEVENOS_TERMINAL_TRANSPARENT=0 seven-terminal` starts solid;
- `SEVENOS_TERMINAL_ALPHA=0.70 seven-terminal` tunes opacity.

## SevenOS Mini OS

Each profile is an autonomous mini OS with four layers:

- Kernel Layer: resources, performance, slices.
- Runtime Layer: services, tools, apps.
- Experience Layer: theme, SevenOS bar, surfaces.
- Intelligence Layer: SevenAI behavior and context.

Profiles:

- Equinox: balanced daily use.
- Baobab: African cultural mini OS with digital village, heritage, languages, oral stories, sound, map, fashion, food and offline memory.
- Forge DevOps: development, SDKs, containers, services, deployments and logs.
- Shield: authorized cybersecurity, audit, forensic and sandbox.
- Studio: creator tools, logos, video, audio and design.
- Atlas: documents, maps, OCR, references, trips and local research.
- Pulse: Linux gaming, Proton, low latency and overlays.

What each mini OS separates:

| Element | Separation |
| --- | --- |
| User data | profiled folders and explicit grants |
| HOME/cache/data | per-profile spaces under `profile-containers` |
| Rootfs | separate sealed and verified rootfs per profile |
| Commands | shims and profiled PATH |
| Launchers | profiled `.desktop` files when available |
| Services | active/inactive policy per mini OS |
| UI | adapted Waybar, Dock, Terminal, files and actions |

What remains shared by design:

- kernel;
- Hyprland graphical session;
- GPU;
- low-level network;
- physical pacman;
- some global system services.

SevenOS does not try to be a set of VMs. The goal is strong functional
independence with explicit collaboration when a profile needs a capability or
external folder.

Commands:

```bash
seven profile status
seven profile current
seven profile activate forge
seven profile center forge
seven profile open forge
seven profile apps forge
seven profile grant-folder forge /home/seven/Code/OS/SevenOS --name SevenOS --rw
seven profile folders forge
seven profile open-folder forge /home/seven/Code/OS/SevenOS
seven profile aliases
seven profile migrate-aliases --apply
seven profile health --json
```

To open a folder outside the current mini OS without weakening isolation,
grant it explicitly to the target profile. It appears inside the container at
`/external/<name>` and can be opened as a workspace with
`seven profile open-folder`.

Examples:

```bash
seven profile grant-folder forge /home/seven/Code/OS/SevenOS --name SevenOS --rw
seven profile open-folder forge /home/seven/Code/OS/SevenOS
seven profile folders forge
```

## Recommended Usage By Mini OS

| Mini OS | Use for | Typical actions |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Equinox | daily work, browsing, documents | files, web, settings, dock |
| Forge | code, Git, services, containers | Forge terminal, projects, logs, build |
| Shield | authorized audit, security, sandbox | hash, network, isolation, reports |
| Studio | media, design, assets | images, audio, video, exports |
| Baobab | culture, reading, collections | reader, documents, local memory |
| Pulse | games, captures, performance | Steam, Lutris, recorder, overlays |
| Atlas | Atlas Explorer | documents, maps, OCR, references and local research |

Pulse keeps gaming tools inside the Pulse mini OS when possible:

```bash
seven pulse doctor
seven pulse plan --json
seven pulse install
seven pulse rootfs
seven-pulse launchers
seven-pulse hud
seven-pulse helper
seven pulse activate
seven pulse open
sevenpkg pulse install steam --source pacman
sevenpkg pulse install lutris gamescope mangohud --source pacman
sevenpkg pulse helper paru
sevenpkg pulse install heroic-games-launcher-bin --source paru
sevenpkg pulse limits
```

GPU drivers, kernel modules, Mesa and multilib remain host-level Equinox
responsibilities because the Linux kernel and GPU stack are shared by every mini
OS. `seven pulse doctor` shows the driver guidance without exposing users to
guesswork.

## Mini OS Collaboration

Golden rule: no profile dependency, only explicit collaboration.

Example: Equinox can stay active while borrowing Forge capabilities for development.

```bash
seven mini-os status
seven mini-os suggest
seven mini-os plan equinox forge shield
seven mini-os activate equinox forge --yes
seven mini-os activate equinox --yes
```

Runtime commands:

```bash
seven runtime status
seven runtime plan baobab shield forge
seven runtime activate equinox forge --apply --yes
```

## SevenOS Applications

### Seven Files

SevenOS file manager: tabs, split view, Quick Look, tags, search, trash,
operations, decision inspector, authorized external folders and mini OS
adaptation.

```bash
seven-files
seven-files profile
seven-files reader ~/Documents/book.pdf
```

### Seven Reader

Local PDF/EPUB/document reading with search, book mode and Seven Files
integration.

```bash
seven-reader
seven-reader open ~/Documents/book.pdf
seven reader --json
```

### SevenStore

SevenOS store to install, open, verify and discover apps by mini OS. It uses
`sevenpkg`, Flatpak, pacman/AUR and profiled requirements.

```bash
seven-store
seven store search vlc
seven store detail vlc
seven store apps
```

### Seven Terminal

Native SevenOS terminal with Prism identity: by default it follows the active
mini OS, shows the active vertex in the top bar and keeps advanced modes inside
a sectioned palette. The prompt is minimal by default; detailed context returns
with `SEVENOS_TERMINAL_PROMPT_DETAIL=1`.

```bash
seven-terminal
seven-terminal -- btop
seven-terminal forge
seven-terminal menu
```

Internal shortcuts:

| Action | Shortcut |
| --- | --- |
| New tab | Ctrl+Shift+T |
| Close tab/pane | Ctrl+Shift+W |
| Search | Ctrl+Shift+F |
| Palette | Ctrl+Shift+P or Ctrl+Shift+Space |
| Transparent/solid | Ctrl+Shift+B |
| Text zoom | Ctrl+Plus / Ctrl+Minus / Ctrl+0 |

Useful variables:

```bash
SEVENOS_TERMINAL_PROMPT_DETAIL=1 seven-terminal
SEVENOS_TERMINAL_TRANSPARENT=0 seven-terminal
SEVENOS_TERMINAL_CLEAN=0 seven-terminal
```

### SevenAI

Local-first SevenOS assistant. It can diagnose, explain, prepare actions and ask
for confirmation before sensitive changes.

```bash
seven-ai
seven ai focus
seven ai diagnose system --json
seven ai "prepare a Forge space for coding"
```

### seven and sevenpkg

`seven` orchestrates the OS. `sevenpkg` manages SevenOS software layers and
meta-packages.

Installation model:

- Equinox uses the global system scope: pacman, yay, paru and Arch packages can
  serve as the shared base.
- Forge, Shield, Studio, Baobab, Atlas and Pulse install packages inside
  their profiled root when you use `sevenpkg --profile`.
- Apps installed inside one mini OS do not pollute the other mini OS profiles.
- Apps installed globally by Equinox can be exposed to mini OS profiles only
  when SevenOS decides it or the user authorizes it.

```bash
seven --help
sevenpkg status
sevenpkg plan --json
sevenpkg profile-limits
sevenpkg install --profile forge htop --source pacman --preview
sevenpkg install --profile studio blender --source paru --preview
sevenpkg remove --profile forge htop --preview
sevenpkg install forge
sevenpkg transaction plan forge --json
```

## System Manual

This section groups the operations that should stay local to SevenOS. It exists
so users do not need to search the web when part of the system is unclear.

### Settings And Public Surfaces

| Need | Surface | Command |
| --- | --- | --- |
| General settings | SevenOS Settings | `seven settings` |
| Remove an app without terminal | Settings > Removal | `seven settings` |
| Install an app | SevenStore | `seven store` |
| Launch an app or action | Spotlight | `seven spotlight` |
| See mini OS profiles | SevenOS Home | `seven home` |
| Switch mini OS | Profile Center | `seven profile center` |
| Local help | Help Center | `seven-help-native` |

### Network And Wi-Fi

SevenOS uses NetworkManager underneath, but users should use SevenOS Settings,
Quick Settings or `seven network`.

```bash
seven network status
seven network status --json
seven network repair
seven network repair --yes
./install.sh network --yes
seven-wifi status-json
seven-quick-settings wifi
```

If Wi-Fi does not appear after installing on a new machine:

1. Run `./install.sh network --yes`.
2. Reboot if a driver or NetworkManager was just installed.
3. Check with `seven network status`.
4. Open `seven-quick-settings wifi` to connect.
5. Run `seven post-install` to confirm SevenOS sees the network.

### Fonts And macOS-Like Rendering

SevenOS keeps typography roles in the system so the visual result does not
depend on the machine used for installation.

```bash
seven fonts status
seven fonts status --json
seven fonts apply-default
seven fonts import ~/Downloads/MyFont.ttf
seven fonts import ~/Downloads/FontFolder
seven fonts refresh
seven fonts prefs
seven fonts open
```

If a font is not applied:

1. Run `seven fonts apply-default`.
2. Run `seven fonts refresh`.
3. Close and reopen the affected app.
4. Run `seven post-install` to check for missing font packages.

### French / English Languages

SevenOS keeps two default system packs: US English and France French. The UI
language is separate from keyboard layouts, regional formats and mini OS
profiles, so switching language does not break shortcuts or isolated profiles.

```bash
seven language status
seven language status --json
seven language doctor
seven language doctor --json
seven language list
seven language set fr_FR.UTF-8
seven language set en_US.UTF-8
seven language apply --live
```

Remember:

1. `seven language doctor` checks FR/EN catalogs, the ISO, installer, generated
   locales and the Waybar indicator.
2. `seven language set ...` changes the language for new windows and terminals.
3. `seven language apply --live` restarts visible SevenOS surfaces.
4. Keyboard layouts stay managed by `seven keyboard apply`, not by the language.
5. Waybar displays `FR` or `EN` dynamically through `seven-waybar-language`.

If one app stays in the old language, close and reopen that app. If the whole
session still feels inconsistent, run `seven language doctor`, then `seven
language apply --live`.

### Theme, Wallpaper And Boot

```bash
./install.sh theme dark
./install.sh theme light
seven theme doctor
seven-wallpaper status
seven-wallpaper refresh
seven-wallpaper collection-list
seven-wallpaper collection prism-dawn
seven-wallpaper rotation set 900 prism-dawn aurora-night terra-golden
seven-wallpaper rotation preset day 900
seven-wallpaper rotation preset calm 1800
seven-wallpaper rotation status
seven-wallpaper rotation off
./install.sh branding
seven login-theme status
seven login-theme doctor
./install.sh boot-splash
./install.sh login-theme
```

The SevenOS theme synchronizes GTK, Qt, terminal, Waybar, Rofi, Mako, wallpaper
and icons. If only one app looks wrong, start with `seven theme doctor`. If the
whole interface looks wrong, use `seven repair ux --apply`.
The Plymouth splash is generated from the active system language (`fr` or `en`)
when running `seven boot-splash apply` or `seven boot-splash theme`. It also
injects the active Mini OS into the boot chip so SevenOS identity stays
coherent from startup.
The SevenOS SDDM login screen is configured with `seven login-theme apply`; it
uses the Prism, Hyprland identity and active Qt locale without changing users or
passwords.
`seven-wallpaper collection-list` shows the 45 SevenOS dynamic wallpapers.
They are also available in Settings > Wallpaper > SevenOS Collection.
In that gallery, enable `Rotation selection`, choose multiple wallpapers, set
the delay and start rotation. `seven-wallpaper rotation set 900 ...` keeps the
rotation persistent for the active mini OS, including after reboot; `rotation
off` disables it.
The `day`, `calm`, `focus`, `night` and `vivid` presets provide a coherent
rotation without building the list manually.

### Stable Waybar And Lock Screen

```bash
seven-waybar status --json
seven-waybar limits --json
seven-waybar doctor --json
seven-waybar restart
seven-waybar stable
seven-waybar dynamic
seven-profile-theme audit-waybars
```

Waybar is generated from the active profile and mini OS profiles keep their own
configs under `~/.config/sevenos/profiles/*/waybar`. To avoid visual changes on
every window focus event, SevenOS can keep context signals stable:

```ini
# ~/.config/sevenos/waybar.conf
context=stable
signal_min_interval=3.0
```

The lock screen shows the connected user through `$USER`. Reapplying the theme
keeps this behavior from `hyprland/hyprlock.conf` and
`hyprland-light/hyprlock.conf`.

### Updates, Health And Recovery

```bash
./install.sh system-install --yes
seven update
seven update check
seven update install --yes
seven update rollback
seven upgrade --yes
seven update --json
seven release review
seven release open
seven release freeze --json
seven quality
seven quality doctor
seven lifecycle
seven health
seven recovery
seven support
seven state --json
seven events --limit 30
```

SevenOS prefers `seven update`, `seven recovery` and `seven health` over direct
backend commands for users. Arch commands remain available in Equinox for
system administration.
On public machines, SevenOS lives in `/opt/SevenOS`; `seven update install`
creates a rollback snapshot, updates that tree, backs up protected state,
refreshes commands and then applies system/app updates.
A readable report is written to
`~/.local/state/sevenos/update/last-report.json`, then SevenOS gently refreshes
Waybar, notifications and Dock without forcing a new login.
`./install.sh system-install --yes` is the route that places or refreshes this
system tree and the commands available from anywhere.
`seven release review` groups modified/untracked files before the public freeze.
`seven release open` opens the same review as a native surface, then
`seven release freeze --json` writes the manifest with `git-status.txt` and
`diff-stat.txt` paths.
`seven quality doctor` combines the gates that matter for a public experience:
health, native surfaces, smoke, update, mini OS, Shell AGS, Server/Deploy and
release freeze.

### Backup And Migration

```bash
./install.sh migrate-plan
./install.sh migrate-backup
seven manifest
seven cloud
seven cloud --json
```

Before a major change, run `./install.sh migrate-plan`. To protect SevenOS user
state, run `./install.sh migrate-backup`.

### ISO, Installer And Release Channel

```bash
./install.sh installer-stack --yes
./install.sh iso-tools --yes
./install.sh iso
seven installer status
seven installer plan
seven installer runtime
seven installer iso-runtime
seven installer iso-runtime deps --yes
seven installer iso-runtime build-local-repo --dry-run
seven installer iso-runtime build-local-repo --yes
seven release
seven channel
seven distribution
```

SevenOS can be a good test machine before it is a public ISO. The
`seven distribution` command says whether the current state looks like a daily
driver distribution, a release candidate or a development layer.
For a public graphical ISO, `seven installer iso-runtime` checks that
Calamares is declared in the ISO and that the local package repository is ready.

## Packages And Install

SevenOS separates three cases:

| Case | Where to install | Recommended command |
| --- | --- | --- |
| App for the whole system | Equinox/global | `sevenpkg install --global <pkg>` |
| App for one mini OS | profile rootfs | `sevenpkg install --profile forge <pkg>` |
| Public graphical app | SevenStore | `seven store` |

Useful commands:

```bash
sevenpkg search vlc
sevenpkg info forge
sevenpkg status
sevenpkg sources
sevenpkg doctor
sevenpkg plan
sevenpkg optional
sevenpkg history
sevenpkg owner nmap
sevenpkg profile-limits
sevenpkg profile-limits forge
sevenpkg profile-packages
sevenpkg profile-packages forge --query htop
sevenpkg global-policy mongodb
sevenpkg global-expose mongodb --profiles forge --commands mongod mongosh
sevenpkg global-expose mongodb --all-mini-os --commands mongod mongosh
sevenpkg global-restrict mongodb
sevenpkg global-clear mongodb
sevenpkg profile-service mongodb forge
sevenpkg profile-service mongodb forge --enable --start
sevenpkg profile-service status forge mongodb
sevenpkg profile-service remove forge mongodb
sevenpkg install --profile shield nmap --source pacman --preview
sevenpkg install --profile studio blender --source paru --preview
sevenpkg profile-install forge nodejs npm --source pacman --preview
sevenpkg profile-remove forge nodejs --preview
sevenpkg remove --profile forge htop --preview
sevenpkg update --profile forge --preview
sevenpkg update --global --preview
```

Important rules:

- Equinox is the admin space: it can use pacman, yay and paru directly.
- Mini OS profiles should use `sevenpkg --profile` to keep packages private.
- Installing into Forge, Shield, Studio, Baobab, Atlas or Pulse writes to the
  target mini OS rootfs, then SevenOS verifies and reseals that rootfs.
- Installing into Equinox writes to the host. The package stays Equinox-only by
  default unless `sevenpkg global-expose` exposes selected commands to one or
  more mini OS profiles.
- `sevenpkg global-restrict <pkg>` disables host exposure to mini OS profiles.
- `sevenpkg global-clear <pkg>` removes the explicit policy entry.
- For a private daemon such as MongoDB, use `sevenpkg profile-service mongodb
  forge`: the user systemd unit starts `mongod` inside the Forge rootfs and
  stores data in `/profile/data/mongodb`.
- Add `--enable --start` to enable and start the service; without `--start`,
  SevenOS only creates the unit for inspection.
- `--preview` shows the impact before changing anything.
- Removing from a mini OS is blocked if the package is not installed inside its
  rootfs.
- `sevenpkg profile-limits` explains what each profile allows.
- `sevenpkg profile-packages` shows what is actually installed by profile.

## Security, Shield And Atlas

### Shield And Security

Shield is for authorized use: audit, forensic, sandboxing, reports, analysis and
hardening. It does not replace legal or professional rules; it organizes tools
so the main OS remains stable.

```bash
seven shield status
seven shield plan
seven shield audit
seven shield tools
seven shield lab --preset web
seven shield lab --preset forensics
./install.sh security --yes
./install.sh cybersecurity core --yes
./install.sh cybersecurity sandbox --yes
```

For specialized BlackArch tools:

```bash
./install.sh blackarch-setup --dry-run
./install.sh blackarch-setup --yes
seven shield toolchain blackarch-full --dry-run
seven shield toolchain blackarch-full --yes
./install.sh blackarch-category webapp --dry-run
./install.sh blackarch-tool feroxbuster --dry-run
```

BlackArch is intentionally optional because it adds an external repository. The
full package set is massive: use `--dry-run` first, then `--yes` only on a
dedicated Shield workstation.

### Atlas Explorer

Atlas replaces the old Windows vertex: SevenOS now keeps seven native mini OS
identities without depending on a Windows VM. Atlas is for documents, maps, OCR,
references, trips, archives and local research.

```bash
seven atlas open
seven atlas status
seven atlas install --yes
seven profile activate atlas
seven profile open atlas
seven profile apps atlas
seven profile requirements atlas --optional --apply --yes
```

`seven atlas status` explains what is missing. `seven atlas install --yes` installs
the essential packages. Optional requirements add Anki, Recoll, Zeal, QGIS/JOSM
or other advanced tools depending on enabled repositories.

## Local FAQ

### Why does SevenOS say not to put sudo before install.sh?

The installer needs to know the real user to write files into the right HOME,
prepare mini OS profiles, apply fonts and create user services. Run
`./install.sh new-device --yes` as a normal user: SevenOS asks for admin rights
only for pacman, system services or protected files.

### Why does Wi-Fi not work after install?

On a fresh machine, network packages, NetworkManager, the service or firmware
may be missing. Run:

```bash
./install.sh network --yes
seven network status
seven-quick-settings wifi
```

If a driver was just installed, reboot and run `seven post-install`.

### Why does the font not look identical to macOS?

SevenOS does not copy macOS; it applies a coherent and stable font stack. If a
machine is missing fonts or cache refresh:

```bash
seven fonts apply-default
seven fonts refresh
seven fonts status
```

### Where should I install software?

If the software is for the whole system, install it in Equinox/global. If it
belongs to one mini OS, install it into that profile.

```bash
sevenpkg install --global firefox --preview
sevenpkg install --profile forge nodejs --source pacman --preview
sevenpkg install --profile studio blender --source paru --preview
```

### Why does an app installed in Forge not appear in Studio?

That is intentional. Mini OS profiles have separate roots and inventories. To
share a global app, install it from Equinox/global and let SevenOS expose it to
profiles that need it.

### How do I remove an app without terminal?

Open `seven settings`, go to Removal, choose the profile, then remove from the
interface. The terminal equivalent is:

```bash
sevenpkg remove --profile forge <package> --preview
```

### How do I know whether SevenOS is broken or just incomplete?

Start with fast diagnostics:

```bash
seven status
seven doctor
seven post-install
seven health
seven insights
```

If the problem is visual, run `seven repair ux --apply`. If it is system-level,
check `seven recovery`.

### Why does SevenOS still mention Arch, pacman or Hyprland?

SevenOS uses those technologies as foundations. Public users should use SevenOS
Settings, SevenStore, `seven` and `sevenpkg`. Equinox keeps admin access to Arch
tools so advanced users are not locked out.

### Where is mini OS data stored?

Profiles have dedicated folders under SevenOS state and profile containers.
External folders must be added explicitly:

```bash
seven profile grant-folder forge ~/Project --name Project --rw
seven profile folders forge
seven profile open-folder forge ~/Project
```

### How do I return to a clean interface?

```bash
seven repair ux --apply
seven hypr apply
seven theme doctor
seven-wallpaper refresh
```

## SevenOS Glossary

| Term | Practical meaning |
| --- | --- |
| Equinox | main/admin/daily profile with HOME and global package access |
| Mini OS | specialized space such as Forge, Shield, Studio, Baobab, Atlas or Pulse |
| Active profile | mini OS currently used by interface and actions |
| Profile rootfs | private root where a mini OS can install packages |
| Global scope | system-visible install managed by Equinox |
| Profile scope | install limited to one mini OS |
| Grant | explicit permission to share an external folder with a profile |
| Bridge | controlled passage between mini OS profiles |
| SevenStore | graphical surface to install and manage apps |
| sevenpkg | SevenOS manager above pacman, yay, paru, Flatpak and profiles |
| SevenOS Settings | normal-user control center |
| SevenOS Home | visual front door for mini OS profiles |
| Spotlight | global search for apps, actions and files |
| Shield | authorized cybersecurity and sandbox profile |
| Atlas Explorer | documents, maps, OCR, references and trips |
| Recovery | SevenOS repair and restore route |
| Post-install | check for dependencies, services, fonts, network and surfaces |

